  {
    "id": "builder_blog:builder_blog:https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/4/building-a-world-map-with-only-500-bytes/#atom-everything",
    "source": "builder_blog",
    "sourceItemId": "builder_blog:https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/4/building-a-world-map-with-only-500-bytes/#atom-everything",
    "title": "Building a World Map with only 500 bytes",
    "summary": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.experimentlog.com/blog/building-a-world-map-with-only-500-bytes\">Building a World Map with only 500 bytes</a></strong></p> Iwo Kadziela (assisted by Codex) figured out a way to generate a credible ASCII world map using 445 bytes of data:</p> <p><img alt=\"A map of the world rendered as black asterisk ASCII characters, it looks very good\" src=\"https://static.simonwillison.net/static/2026/world-map-ascii.png\" /></p> <p>The key trick is to use deflate compression, whi",
    "body": "<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.experimentlog.com/blog/building-a-world-map-with-only-500-bytes\">Building a World Map with only 500 bytes</a></strong></p> Iwo Kadziela (assisted by Codex) figured out a way to generate a credible ASCII world map using 445 bytes of data:</p> <p><img alt=\"A map of the world rendered as black asterisk ASCII characters, it looks very good\" src=\"https://static.simonwillison.net/static/2026/world-map-ascii.png\" /></p> <p>The key trick is to use deflate compression, which is then wired together using this neat snippet of JavaScript. I didn't know you could use <code>fetch()</code> with <code>data:</code> URIs like this:</p> <pre><code>fetch('data:;base64,1ZpLsgIxCEXnrM...==').then( r => r.body.pipeThrough(new DecompressionStream('deflate-raw')) ).then( s => new Re",
    "url": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/Jul/4/building-a-world-map-with-only-500-bytes/#atom-everything",
    "sourceName": "Simon Willison",
    "sourceCategory": "technical",
